<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-065-376  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 065 376.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>MIS Week  Jan 15 1990 v10 n3 p30(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Optical storage moves closer to 'the blues' with laser discovery.andO;(blue laser optical storage for computers)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Boyle, Bob.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The next generation of computers will be optical, but a blue lasercapable of traveling faster and carrying more information than anyother color laser will be used.andP;  University of Florida (UF) isresearching and developing such a laser, as are IBM and HiroshimaUniversity in Japan.andP;  IBM does not believe anyone will besuccessful in developing such a laser, but has been attempting todo so by mixing different laser colors.andP;  Hiroshima Universitydeveloped a zinc selenide laser, one step toward making a bluelaser, but it had to be cooled to minus 93 degrees.andP;  In Dec 1989,UF made a breakthrough by producing the first optically poweredlaser made from zinc selenide that operated at room temperature.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   International Business Machines Corp. (research).andO;Ticker:    IBM.andO;Topic:     LasersColorResearch and DevelopmentTechnologyJapanese CompetitionUniversity of FloridaFuture of ComputingOptical MemoryPerformanceMemoryInventions.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>